NAME
    environ(4)     	- description of the user environment

SYNOPSIS
    extern  char  **environ;

DESCRIPTION
    Using execve() a list of strings may be passed to a new process.
    The new process may use either the global variable "environ", or
    the third parameter in "main(argc,argv,envp)" to point to a list
    of (char *) pointers. These pointers each refer to a string of
    characters, terminated by a '\0'. The last pointer is NULL. By
    convention the strings are of the form: "NAME=VALUE".

    Entries can be looked up using getenv(3). Entries can be changed
    or added using putenv(3).

    The environment may be changed from within the shell. (Note that
    the "export" command flags names which should be put in the user
    environment.) The environment may be looked at using printenv(1),
    or a $NAME escape to the shell. The more notable names are,

    PATH    Where to search for commands. Set by a login shell to
            ":/bin:/usr/bin". May be reset in the ".profile" file.

    HOME    Used by the "cd" command in "sh". Set by "login" and "su"
            to the entry given in the password file. 

    SHELL   Set by "login" and "su" to the entry given in the password
            file (default is "/bin/sh"). 

    TERM
    TERMCAP Used by the termcap routines to determine the terminal's
            type.

    IFS
    PS1
    PS2     Used by "sh". These are not automatically exported.

FILES
    ~/.profile
    /etc/passwd

SEE ALSO
    login(1), printenv(1), sh(1), su(1), tset(1), execve(2)
    getenv(3), putenv(3), termcap(3), termcap(4)
